User survey for ImagingSociety 2025 - National MRI research infrastructure in Norway

Author

Dr. Athanasia M. Mowinckel

Published

October 2, 2025

Background

This report presents an analysis of the survey data collected for the national grant scheme application for MRI research infrastructure in Norway. The survey was designed to gather insights from the research community on the current use, needs, and challenges related to MRI for human research.

The following sections will present a summary of the key findings, including graphical representations of the quantitative data and a textual summary of the open-ended responses, with the help of the Gemini LMM.

Survey Results

Of the 64 responses, 29 participants reported they currently use MRI for research, 45% indicate a future interest in using the new MRI facility for their work.

Participant Demographics

This section provides an overview of the survey participants’ roles and institutions.

Research Areas

The survey respondents represent a diverse range of research areas, with a strong emphasis on cognitive neuroscience and neuroscience. Key areas include:

  • Cognitive Neuroscience: This appears to be the most prevalent area, covering topics such as attention, decision-making, learning, language, music, predictive processing, and general cognitive functions.
  • Neuroscience: A broad category including general neuroscience research, as well as more specific areas like brain connectivity, metabolism, neurochemistry, and neurodegeneration.
  • Mental Health: Includes research on mental disorders, psychotherapy, psychosis, mood disorders, child and adolescent psychiatry, anorexia nervosa, and related neurodevelopmental disorders.
  • Aging and Dementia: A significant area of focus, covering healthy aging, dementia, Alzheimer’s disease, cerebrovascular disease, and cognitive decline.
  • Neurology: Encompasses various neurological conditions such as multiple sclerosis, stroke, epilepsy, brain tumors, and headache research.
  • Brain Injury and Rehabilitation: Includes research on brain injury in sport, rehabilitation medicine, and related topics.
  • Specific Populations and Conditions: Also included are autoimmune diseases like lupus, women’s health issues like menopause and menstrual cycle related symptoms, pain research, speech and language processing, visual impairments, and more.
  • Methodological Approaches: A variety of methods are mentioned, including brain imaging (MRI, fNIRS, EEG), pupillometry, eye-tracking, computational modelling, and genetics.
  • Interdisciplinary Areas: Some respondents are working in interdisciplinary fields, such as psychophysiology, human-computer interaction, environmental psychology, and even applying medical imaging techniques to paleoclimatology.

How MRI Would Enhance Research

Based on the survey responses, increased access to MRI would significantly expand and improve research in several key areas:

  • Improved capacity: Many researchers expressed the need for increased capacity and research dedicated scanner availability.
  • Understanding brain structure, function, and connectivity: MRI is crucial for investigating a wide range of neurological and psychiatric conditions, cognitive functions (memory, attention, language, etc.), brain development across the lifespan, and the impact of interventions (brain stimulation, therapies).
  • Investigating specific conditions: This includes, but is not limited to, sexual dysfunctions, concussions, dementia (Alzheimer’s, Lewy body), eating disorders, neurodevelopmental disorders, ADHD (especially in women and the impact of hormonal changes), SLE, epilepsy, MS, chronic pain (oral pain), spinal cord disorders, and brain tumors.
  • Developing and validating novel algorithms and models: Several researchers use MRI to develop new analytical techniques and models for understanding brain function and disease.
  • Enhancing clinical decision-making and treatment development: MRI provides clinically relevant information for diagnosis, tracking disease progression, and developing targeted therapies, including personalized treatments based on individual brain characteristics.
  • Enabling multi-center collaborations and larger sample sizes: Greater access would facilitate participation in national and international collaborative studies, leading to more robust and generalizable findings.
  • Expanding research methodologies: Researchers are interested in using MRI to complement other methods like EEG, EMG, and behavioral measures, integrating anatomical and functional data for a more comprehensive understanding. Some are interested in restarting stalled MRI research or starting new lines of inquiry.
  • Attracting funding: Lack of MRI access is cited as a barrier to securing grant funding, with researchers needing access to pilot data and experience to strengthen their applications.
  • Geohazard detection: One respondent suggests using MRI as a novel technique to “diagnose” geohazards.

Future Needs

This section analyzes which conditions are considered most important for the future of MRI research in Norway.

Summary of Free-text Comments

This section provides a summary of the open-ended comments, generated using the Gemini LMM.

These survey responses express strong support for expanding MRI research capabilities in Norway, emphasizing accessibility, collaboration, and advanced technology. A key theme is the desire for increased research focus, potentially through prioritizing research time or offering more competitive pricing. Specifically, there is a desire for an MRI scanner located outside of a hospital setting, ideally near the University of Bergen, to facilitate innovative research approaches and improve accessibility for researchers. Building a collaborative MRI research community, particularly in Tromsø, is seen as vital. Finally, respondents advocate for standardized capabilities across sites, consistent scheduling for researchers, and the acquisition of at least one 7T scanner for specialized subcortical research, drawing inspiration from successful large-scale initiatives like the UK Biobank.

Conclusion

In conclusion, the overwhelming sentiment expressed in this survey underscores a critical need for increased access to research-dedicated MRI scanners across Norway. Participants across various institutions, research roles, and disciplines highlighted how limited access currently hinders their ability to conduct innovative and impactful research. Whether it be a lack of scanner time, insufficient funding, or a shortage of skilled personnel, the challenges are clear. Investing in more research-focused MRI infrastructure, coupled with strategic resource allocation and collaborative networks, would not only address these existing barriers but also unlock significant potential for groundbreaking discoveries, enhance Norway’s position in the international research landscape, and ultimately improve the health and well-being of the population. This survey serves as a powerful call to action, urging stakeholders to prioritize and invest in the vital resource that is research-focused MRI.
